Stack&#39;s answer addresses the potential of embedding Heritrix inside your
own Java launcher/service wrapper; another possibility is to use it as
a command-line tool.

You can supply a premade order.xml file on the Heritrix command-line.
If you also use the -r/--run option, the crawler will immediately
start crawling pending jobs (such as the one just supplied); you can
even suppress the launch of the web UI with -n/--nowui.

This was the initial way to launch crawls before the web UI was
developed. Since we no longer make regular use of this facility, it
doesn&#39;t offer the same level of monitoring and control of the crawl,
but might be useful for launching crawls as a subpart of some larger
system, especially small crawls unlikely to need all administration options.

If you were to make significant use of this mode of operation, you might
want to add better feedback on crawl progress or ways to add/pause/adjust/cancel
crawls from the command-line. See for example the RFE:

   [ 894467 ] Stopping, pausing, checkpointing from cmdline
   http://sourceforge.net/tracker/index.php?func=detail&aid=894467&group_id=73833&atid=539102

If you add any capabilities here you can contribute to the codebase, let
us know!

- Gordon @ IA

